<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920103-0051</DOCNO><DOCID>920103-0051.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Saint Louis S.A.:   Stake of 53.89% in Concern   Is Held by Two Companies</HL><DATE>01/03/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3B</SO><CO>   F.STL I.IFL</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)FINANCIAL (FIN)CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)RAW AND FINISHED PAPER PRODUCTS (PAP)SECURITIES (SCR)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>EUROPE (EU)FRANCE (FR)ITALY (ITA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   French investment group Worms andamp; Cie. and IFIL Finanziariode Partecipazioni S.p.A. of Italy together own 53.89% ofFrench food and paper group Saint Louis S.A., the Frenchstock market authority announced.   The Societe des Bourses Francaises said Worms and IFILinformed Bourse authorities Nov. 20, 1991, that they were&quot;acting in concert within Saint Louis&quot; and had surpassed 50%of Saint Louis's voting rights. This requires an officialdeclaration, according to French Bourse rules.</LP><TEXT>   The SBF noted that it decided on Dec. 4 to exempt Wormsand Saint Louis from launching a takeover bid for the entirecompany, reasoning that Worms, with nearly 50% itself,already had effective control over the company.   A breakdown of the two companies' stakes revealed thatWorms controls 49.454%, while IFIL has 4.45%.   Officials at Saint Louis, Worms and IFIL weren't availablefor comment.</TEXT></DOC>